snippet.textDisplay:
) The Fairfax County Board of Supervisors in Virginia passed a motion on July 16, 2019, to alert local residents about traveling to China for organ transplant surgeries. Board members put forward the motion because Falun Gong practitioners and other prisoners of conscience in China have become victims of forced organ harvesting, and the board felt that local Fairfax residents and local medical staff needed to become aware of that.

The motion was initiated by chairwoman Sharon Bulova along with board members John Cook, John Foust, and Pat Herrity. It was then passed unanimously by all members of the board.


The Fairfax County Board of Supervisors passed a motion on July 16, 2019, condemning forced organ harvesting in China and alerting residents about traveling to China for organ transplant.

Chairwoman: Forced Organ Harvesting Is 'Gruesome' And 'Awful'

John Cook introduced the board item.

Cook, in giving background of the motion, presented the U.S. House Resolution 343, which was passed by the House of Representatives on June 13, 2016, to condemn forced organ harvesting in China. He said the resolution was on a bipartisan basis with all Northern Virginia Representatives’ support.

As local officials, “We are concerned—as are our local Falun Gong practitioners—that people who go to China for organ transplants, which are much more available in China than in the United States,” he said.

This is because people “do not know that the organs they receive may be from Falun Gong practitioners or other political prisoners who are murdered so the communist government may benefit from the sale of their organs,” Cook said.

He hoped the county could inform residents about the issue so people could make an educated decision not to travel to China for a transplant.

snippet.textDisplay: I am frankly vary disappointed in you Phill, you normally cover both sides of an issue. in the last week particular you seem to be running from any objective analyses and giving in to fear. everything you say is stay home and that will save lives. where is the analyses over how long can we realistically shut down en economy before the loss to life later is greater than the short term. your own video tells us there will not be a vaccine for over a year. So what is the goal? how much testing, how many respirators do we need, how long will that take, and how long for insentience before the loss to the economy causes homelessness that leads to deaths do to starvation. last year it is estimated 2 million people lost their lives from starvation and that is in a booming world economy. How many years will that linger? how douse the shutdown affect production of need equipment? last week alone jest after ramping up production of coved testing there was a dip in production of test due to lack of swabs and some of the chemicals needed. Before i get into this i am not say a shutdown is bad but without even an estimate of cost to lives and financial cost in the future you can’t say you are saving any lives. For example, the simplest of medical devices like a face mask. They require materials from 2nd and 3rd party vendors to make them (that people don’t think are critical). The manufacturer of a face mask likely has the machinery to make the face mask but orders the fabric from one 2nd part and the 2nd party likely orders the cotton or material they turn into that fabric from a 3rd part. next there is the thread to stitch the mask together another 2nd part and like they have a 3rd party for cotton . next there is the rubber band to go around the ears another 2nd party to make that and then rubber being a complex material they likely have 3 to 4 vendors they order 3 or 4 chemical to mix and make the rubber, finally there is the packaging to ship the masks in. that is at least one more 2nd part and at least another 3rd party vendor. that is up to 11 companies besides the mask manufacture jest to get the simplest of medical devises. think how many companies are involved in respirators. then think how many things are required to save lives medication. tools. raw materials, people to keep machines tuning and keep going. you can’t jest shut down industry and say your saving lives. estimates say every thing form 40 to 90% of industry plays some part in product that is a necessity. think about that when they talk about shooting down any state.  even luxury goods manufacturers like a tv manufacturer make monitors for medical equipment. we need to analyses every choice we make and if we dont know how many lives that choice will cost or at least have a reasonable estimate then we should not be doing it as we say we are saving lives.

I do retail arbitrage, so that requires me to enter a thrift store or go to a garage sale to purchase goods then ship them to Amazon. I'm not technically an employee nor am I a gig worker. What do people like me wind up getting?
